  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Car Fleet\n\nCars drive toward `target`. A faster car that catches a slower car becomes part of that slower fleet. Return the number of fleets that arrive.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: target = 12, position = [10, 8, 0, 5, 3], speed = [2, 4, 1, 1, 3]\nOutput: 3\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: target = 10, position = [3], speed = [3]\nOutput: 1\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: target = 100, position = [0, 2, 4], speed = [4, 2, 1]\nOutput: 1\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Input sizes follow the original interview-style constraints.\n- Return values must match the described behavior.",
  "editorial": "Use a stack to keep unresolved items. When a new token, bar, or value resolves earlier items, pop them and update the answer.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def carFleet(self, target, position, speed):\n        cars = sorted(zip(position, speed), reverse=True)\n        fleets = 0\n        slowest = 0\n        for pos, spd in cars:\n            time = (target - pos) / spd\n            if time > slowest:\n                fleets += 1\n                slowest = time\n        return fleets\n```",
  "hints": [
    "A stack is useful when the most recent unresolved item should be handled first.",
    "Keep extra state on the stack when constant-time queries are needed."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def carFleet(self, target, position, speed):\n        pass\n"
  },
